  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>One of the most stressful experiences in a property sale is accepting a subject-to-finance offer, having the property off the market for two to three weeks, and then receiving notification that the buyer's finance has been declined. The property goes back to market with a "previously under contract" label that generates questions from new buyers, you have lost momentum, and the buyers who might have offered at the time of first sale have moved on.</p>

      <p>The best protection against this outcome is a clear understanding of your buyer's financial position before you accept their offer. That does not necessarily mean demanding a formal pre-approval letter for every offer, but it does mean your listing agent should be asking the right questions to assess how credible the buyer's finance situation actually is.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What a pre-approval letter actually tells you</h2>
      <p>A finance pre-approval from a bank or lender tells you that the lender has assessed the buyer's income, assets, liabilities, and credit history and has indicated they are willing to lend up to a specified amount, subject to final verification of the property and the buyer's circumstances at the time of formal application.</p>

      <p>The key phrase is "subject to final verification." A pre-approval is not a guaranteed loan. It is a conditional indication of willingness to lend, based on the information provided to the lender at the time of the assessment. Pre-approvals are typically valid for 90 days and can lapse or be revised if the buyer's circumstances change, if interest rates move significantly, if the property does not value up at the required level, or if the lender's credit policies are updated between pre-approval and formal application.</p>

      <p>A pre-approval letter does tell you several things that are useful. It tells you the buyer has engaged a lender, been through a credit assessment, and received a clear indication of their borrowing capacity. It tells you there are no obvious red flags in their financial profile, at least at the time of assessment. A buyer with a current pre-approval from a reputable lender is meaningfully more credible than a buyer who simply says they have spoken to their bank and expects their finance to be fine.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The difference between pre-approval and unconditional approval</h2>
      <p>Pre-approval (also called conditional approval or approval in principle) is the lender's initial assessment. Unconditional approval (also called formal approval) is issued after the lender has assessed the specific property, conducted a valuation, and satisfied all remaining conditions. Unconditional approval means the loan is confirmed and will proceed to settlement.</p>

      <p>When a buyer says they are waiting on their finance clause, they are waiting for formal approval, not pre-approval. A buyer who enters a contract subject to finance with a pre-approval in hand is in a reasonable position but is not yet approved. Finance clauses in Queensland typically run for 14 to 21 days, during which the buyer's broker or lender completes the formal application, orders a valuation of the property, and obtains credit approval.</p>

      <p>The period between pre-approval and formal approval is when deals fall over. Common reasons include a lower-than-expected property valuation, a change in the buyer's employment status, a recent large purchase that affected their debt-to-income ratio, or a change in lender policy. None of these are necessarily visible when you accept the offer.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why sellers should not always insist on a pre-approval letter</h2>
      <p>While pre-approval provides useful comfort, insisting on a letter for every offer can cost you qualified buyers. Some buyers, particularly those purchasing without a mortgage (cash buyers using equity from a previous sale, for instance), will not have a pre-approval letter because they do not need one. Experienced buyers with substantial assets and a long-term banking relationship sometimes move quickly and formally before applying for pre-approval. Requiring documentation before accepting any offer can feel unnecessarily intrusive to credible purchasers and may push them toward a competing listing.</p>

      <p>The better approach is for your listing agent to have a direct conversation with the buyer or their representative to understand their financial situation. How much of the purchase price is being borrowed? Have they spoken to a lender? Have they spoken to a broker? Has a credit assessment been completed? Are they purchasing the property conditional on selling another property first? These questions often reveal more than a pre-approval document, because your agent is having a conversation rather than reading a form letter.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Questions your agent should be asking buyers</h2>
      <p>Before advising you to accept a subject-to-finance offer, a good listing agent should be able to tell you whether the buyer has a pre-approval in place and when it was issued, who their lender or broker is (which gives an indication of how far through the process they are), whether they are purchasing subject to selling another property, what their deposit is and where it is coming from, and how long they anticipate needing to satisfy their finance condition.</p>

      <p>The answers to these questions, combined with the buyer's readiness to exchange at a specific price, give you a reasonable basis for deciding whether to accept their offer, ask for different terms, or wait to see if another buyer who is further along with their finance emerges.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Balancing security with not alienating buyers</h2>
      <p>The goal in assessing buyer financial strength is to make an informed decision, not to audit your buyer's bank accounts. Most buyers expect their agent and the listing agent to have a frank conversation about their finance situation. Requesting a pre-approval letter when there is genuine concern about a buyer's credibility is reasonable. Demanding extensive documentation from every buyer before you will consider their offer is not.</p>

      <p>The practical approach is to let your listing agent do their job. A good agent working in Brisbane's inner east will have seen enough transactions to read a buyer's credibility quickly and advise you accordingly. If they have concerns, they should raise them with you before you accept. If they are confident the buyer is genuine and well-qualified, their assessment is worth more than a piece of paper that contains caveats and expiry dates.</p>

      <p>The risk of a finance failure exists in every subject-to-finance transaction. The goal is not to eliminate that risk entirely, which is impossible, but to accept it only when the buyer has given you reasonable grounds for confidence. A short finance period from a buyer with a current pre-approval from a reputable lender, a credible deposit, and a history of inspecting seriously rather than speculatively, is a materially lower risk than a longer finance period from a buyer who has never spoken to a bank.</p>

